498→pub struct CausalConsistencyProbe;
499→
500→impl Probe for CausalConsistencyProbe {
501→    fn evaluate(&self, state: &EngineState) -> f32 {
502→        let issues = state.lineage_dag_issues();
503→        match issues {
504→            0 => 0.0,
505→            1..=2 => 0.3,
506→            _ => 0.8,
507→        }
508→    }
509→
510→    fn weight(&self) -> f32 { 0.10 }
511→    fn name(&self) -> &str { "causal_consistency" }
512→    fn domain(&self) -> ProbeDomain { ProbeDomain::Universal }
513→}
514→```
515→
516→---
517→
518→## Prediction Error Aggregation
519→
520→The 16 probe results are aggregated into a single prediction error scalar:
521→
522→```
523→prediction_error = Σ(probe_value × probe_weight)    capped at 1.0
524→```
525→
526→The error thresholds for tier routing:
527→
528→```
529→error < 0.2  → T0 (suppress, no LLM)     ~80% of ticks
530→error < 0.6  → T1 (fast model, shallow)   ~15% of ticks
531→error ≥ 0.6  → T2 (full model, deep)      ~5% of ticks
532→```
533→
534→The thresholds (0.2 and 0.6) are the base values. They are adjusted by the adaptive threshold computation (see [08-dual-process-t0-t1-t2.md](./08-dual-process-t0-t1-t2.md)) which modulates based on affect state, resource constraints, and strategy confidence.
535→
536→---
537→
538→## Extensibility: Adding Custom Probes
539→
540→New domains add probes by implementing the `Probe` trait and registering with the `ProbeRegistry`:
541→
542→```rust
543→// Example: a medical domain probe
544→pub struct PatientVitalsProbe;
545→
546→impl Probe for PatientVitalsProbe {
547→    fn evaluate(&self, state: &EngineState) -> f32 {
548→        // Check vital sign deviations from baselines
549→        let deviation = state.custom_metric("patient_vitals_deviation");
550→        deviation.clamp(0.0, 1.0)
551→    }
552→
553→    fn weight(&self) -> f32 { 0.25 }
554→    fn name(&self) -> &str { "patient_vitals" }
555→    fn domain(&self) -> ProbeDomain { ProbeDomain::Custom("medical".into()) }
556→}
557→
558→// Registration at domain plugin initialization
559→registry.register(Box::new(PatientVitalsProbe));
560→```
561→
562→The probe set is composable: users combine whatever probe set matches their domain. A chain agent registers the 8 chain probes + 2 universal probes. A coding agent registers the 6 coding probes + 2 universal probes. A medical agent registers custom medical probes + 2 universal probes. A multi-domain agent registers probes from all relevant domains.
563→
564→---
565→
566→## Academic Foundations
567→
568→- **Chen et al. 2023** — FrugalGPT (arXiv:2305.05176, published 2024 TMLR). Cascade architectures with intelligent routing achieve up to 98% cost reduction while matching top-model quality.
569→- **Friston 2010** — "The Free-Energy Principle" (Nature Reviews Neuroscience 11(2)). Prediction error as the fundamental signal driving attention and action.
570→- **Kahneman 2011** — "Thinking, Fast and Slow" (Farrar, Straus and Giroux). System 1 (probes) handles the majority; System 2 (LLM) handles exceptions.
571→- **Sims 2003** — "Implications of rational inattention" (Journal of Monetary Economics 50(3)). Agents optimally allocate attention based on information value relative to cost.
572→
573→---
574→
575→## Current Status and Gaps
576→
577→**What exists:**
578→- `InferenceTier` enum and `TierRouter` in `bardo-primitives/src/tier.rs`.
579→- The conceptual probe design exists in the PRD documents.
580→- `CascadeRouter` implements three-stage model routing based on observation counts.
581→
582→**What is missing:**
583→- `Probe` trait definition.
584→- `ProbeRegistry` struct and `evaluate_all()` method.
585→- Concrete implementations of all 16 probes.
586→- Integration of probe results into the orchestration loop for tier gating.
587→- Domain plugin registration mechanism for custom probes.
588→- Probe-level telemetry (which probes fire, how often, latency).
589→
590→---
591→
592→## Cross-References
593→
594→- See [08-dual-process-t0-t1-t2.md](./08-dual-process-t0-t1-t2.md) for how probe results drive tier selection
595→- See [04-gamma-reactive-loop.md](./04-gamma-reactive-loop.md) for how probes run in the gamma loop's PERCEIVE step
596→- See [10-active-inference-compute-allocation.md](./10-active-inference-compute-allocation.md) for the theoretical framework behind probe-driven allocation
