## 9. Metacognitive Monitoring: What the Literature Says

The 2024-2025 metacognition literature (CHI 2024, Frontiers in Education 2025) converges on: current LLM systems lack metacognitive awareness — the ability to strategically decide _when_ to think harder vs. accept a fast answer. This is exactly the dual-process gap.

The Mixture-of-Depths (MoD) approach from transformer research provides the cleanest formalism: dynamically allocate transformer compute (depth) per token based on token difficulty. A routing token decides whether each transformer layer is applied or skipped. This is the per-token analog of roko's per-task tier routing.

For roko's CascadeRouter, the actionable version is: before dispatching a task, compute a complexity score from (token count, task category, tool count, cross-crate scope). Use this to predict difficulty band. This is what `TaskComplexityBand` does today — the gap is that the band is set statically in TOML rather than being predicted dynamically. The literature says the best predictor uses mid-layer LLM representations, but a trained lightweight BERT-scale classifier on structured features (token count, category, number of dependencies) achieves ~80% of the accuracy at 0.1% of the cost.

